    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-11-15T08:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-11-15T08:00:00-05:00" n="140"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d140">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">763.72119 P 43/916: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Special Representative</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_HCEM1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">House</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-11-15T13:00:00+00:00"
                            >November 15, 1918—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received November 15—10:31 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>106. Your 34 [<hi rend="italic">33</hi>], November 14 [<hi rend="italic"
                    >13</hi>]. From <persName corresp="#p_GJC1">Grew</persName>. Wish to express my
                    extreme gratification at selection as secretary of United States Commission to
                    Peace Conference and am particularly happy to have <persName corresp="#p_HL2"
                        >Harrison</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_PPH1">Patchin</persName>
                    associated. Arrangements for the representatives are progressing and will take
                    shape as plans of our Commission develop. For the present I foresee no needs
                    which cannot <pb facs="0229" n="159" xml:id="pg_159"/> be met here except
                    insofar as <persName corresp="#p_HCEM1">Colonel House</persName> has made
                    recommendations from time to time, particularly the request Department his 102
                    regarding stationery.<note n="4" xml:id="d140fn4">Not printed.</note> It seems
                    essential that the problems presented in telegrams 52<note n="4"
                        xml:id="d140fn6">Not printed.</note> and 100 [<hi rend="italic"
                        >99?</hi>]<note n="5" xml:id="d140fn5">
                        <hi rend="italic">Post</hi>, <ref target="#pg_194">p. 194</ref>.</note>
                    concerning communication with Washington, political intelligence, etc., should
                    be dealt with in perfect accord and I earnestly hope that the recommendations
                    made therein may be approved as delay in setting the machinery in motion may
                    seriously affect the eventual smooth running of the American organization.</p>
                <p>Would be glad to have <persName corresp="#p_BWC1">Bullitt</persName> come as soon
                    as possible and <persName corresp="#p_DEL1">Dresel</persName> when
                    available.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_HCEM1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Edward House</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
